Date: Fri 23 Nov 2001 12:03:56 -0000
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Agencia EFE (via COMTEX), Wed 21 Nov 2001 [edited

Panama: Greater Panama City on verge of dengue fever epidemic
-------------------------------------------------------------
PANAMA CITY: More than 860 cases of dengue fever and another 6 cases of the
potentially deadly dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) have been reported in
Panama so far this year, placing the country on the verge of an epidemic,
national health authorities warned on Wed 21 Nov 2001. In Panama City 3
cases of DHF have been reported, while the other 3 cases were reported on
the western outskirts of the capital in the La Chorrera district.
Health authorities said 864 cases of the less dangerous variety of dengue
fever have been reported so far this year, most of them in Panama City and
in outlying areas west of the city. A spokesman for the Panamanian Health
Ministry said the area west of Panama City, home to some 150 000 people,
runs the risk of an epidemic of the potentially deadly DHF. The spokesman
said that more than 400 cases of dengue fever have been detected in that
area so far this year.
The symptoms of DHF include headaches, abdominal pains, a high fever,
bleeding from the eyes, and respiratory problems. At first, the symptoms
are easily and often mistaken for influenza. National health authorities
have continuously urged residents to eliminate any potential breeding
grounds for the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, which transmits the disease.
According to official figures from the Health Ministry, a total of 317
cases of dengue fever and one case of DHF, none of which proved deadly,
were reported in Panama in 2000, a number much lower than year-to-date
cases this year.
--
Pablo Nart
<p.nart@virgin.net>
